SIMPLE: tickle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tickle
<hw>Tic"kle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Tickled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tickling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Perhaps freq. of
<ets>tick</ets> to beat; pat; but cf. also AS. <ets>citelian</ets> to
tickle, D. <ets>kittelen</ets>, G. <ets>kitzlen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>chizzil⟦omac⟧n</ets>, <ets>chuzzil⟦omac⟧n</ets>, Icel.
<ets>kitla</ets>. Cf. <er>Kittle</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To touch lightly, so as to produce a peculiar thrilling
sensation, which commonly causes laughter, and a kind of spasm which
become dangerous if too long protracted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If you <qex>tickle</qex> us, do we not laugh?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To please; to gratify; to make joyous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pleased with a rattle, <qex>tickled</qex> with a straw.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such a nature⟦br⟧
<qex>Tickled</qex> with good success, disdains the shadow⟦br⟧
Which he treads on at noon.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tickle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tickle
<hw>Tic"kle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To feel
titillation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He with secret joy therefore⟦br⟧
Did <qex>tickle</qex> inwardly in every vein.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To excite the sensation of titillation.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tickle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tickle
<hw>Tic"kle</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Ticklish; easily
tickled.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Liable to change; uncertain; inconstant.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The world is now full <qex>tickle</qex>, sikerly.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So <qex>tickle</qex> is the state of earthy things.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Wavering, or liable to waver and fall at the
slightest touch; unstable; easily overthrown.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy head stands so <qex>tickle</qex> on thy shoulders, that a
milkmaid, if she be in love, may sigh it off.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tickle-footed</ent>⟦br⟧
